.\" Man page for ruv-gui – Ryzen Undervolt Tool
.\" Format with: groff -man -Tascii ruv-gui.1

.TH RUV-GUI 1 "2026-04-21" "ruv-gui 1.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ruv-gui \- control Ryzen CPU core voltage offsets via the ryzen_smu driver
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ruv-gui
.I COMMAND
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.br
.B ruv-gui
(without arguments launches graphical interface)

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBruv-gui\fR is a command-line and graphical tool to read and set per\-core
voltage offsets on AMD Ryzen CPUs that are supported by the
\fBryzen_smu\fR kernel driver. It can also save and apply profiles, and
set up a systemd service to reapply offsets at boot.

When run without arguments, the graphical user interface (GUI) is launched.
Root privileges are required for most CLI operations; use \fBsudo\fR(8) or run as root.

.SH CORE SPECIFICATION SYNTAX
Many commands accept flexible core specifications:
.TP
\fIsingle core\fR
\fB0\fR, \fB2\fR, \fB5\fR
.TP
\fIcomma\-separated list\fR
\fB0,2,4\fR
.TP
\fIrange (inclusive)\fR
\fB0\-7\fR (all cores from 0 to 7)
.TP
\fIcombination\fR
\fB0,2\-5,7\fR (cores 0, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 7)

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-debug\fR
Enable debug logging (environment variable \fBRUV_DEBUG=1\fR has the same effect).
This option is mainly for internal use and may be suppressed in help output.

.SH COMMANDS

.SS Status and Inspection
.TP
\fBstatus\fR [\fB\-\-json\fR]
Display the current voltage offset (in mV) for each physical core.
With \fB\-\-json\fR, output a JSON object mapping core numbers to offsets.
.TP
\fBget\fR \fICORE_SPEC\fR
Print the current offset for the specified core(s).
Accepts any core specification syntax (e.g., \fB0\fR, \fB0\-3\fR, \fB0,2,4\fR).
.TP
\fBlist\fR
Alias for \fBstatus\fR (provided for internal compatibility).

.SS Modifying Offsets
.TP
\fBset\fR \fICORE_SPEC\fR \fIOFFSET\fR
Set the offset of the specified core(s) to \fIOFFSET\fR mV.
Valid offsets are between \-100 and +100 mV.
Accepts any core specification syntax.
.TP
\fBapply\-list\fR \fICORE_SPEC\fR \fIOFFSET\fR
Apply the same offset to multiple cores without saving a profile.
Functionally similar to \fBset\fR but optimized for bulk operations.
.TP
\fBreset\fR
Reset all core offsets to 0 mV.

.SS Profile Management
Profiles are stored as JSON files under \fI/etc/ruv/profiles/\fR.
.TP
\fBprofile list\fR
List all saved profile names.
.TP
\fBprofile save\fR \fINAME\fR
Save the currently active offsets as a new profile named \fINAME\fR.
Profile names may contain letters, digits, underscores, hyphens, and dots.
.TP
\fBprofile delete\fR \fINAME\fR
Delete the profile \fINAME\fR and optionally reset all offsets to 0
(interactive confirmation).
.TP
\fBprofile apply\fR \fINAME\fR
Apply the offsets stored in profile \fINAME\fR to the CPU.
Alias for \fBapply\fR command.
.TP
\fBprofile read\fR \fINAME\fR
Display the JSON content of profile \fINAME\fR.
Outputs the raw profile data stored in \fI/etc/ruv/profiles/NAME.json\fR.
.TP
\fBprofile update\fR \fINAME\fR \fB\-\-cores\fR \fICORE_SPEC\fR \fB\-\-offset\fR \fIOFFSET\fR [\fB\-\-apply\fR]
Update the offsets of specific cores inside an existing profile.
Accepts any core specification syntax for \fB\-\-cores\fR.
If \fB\-\-apply\fR is given, the new offsets are also applied to the CPU
immediately.
.TP
\fBapply\fR \fINAME\fR
Apply the offsets stored in profile \fINAME\fR to the CPU.
.TP
\fBread\-profile\fR \fIFILE\fR
Legacy command to read a profile by full file path.
Prefer \fBprofile read\fR \fINAME\fR instead.

.SS Boot Service
.TP
\fBboot enable\fR \fINAME\fR
Create and enable a systemd service that applies profile \fINAME\fR
automatically at boot. The service runs once after multi\-user.target.
.TP
\fBboot disable\fR
Disable and remove the boot service.
.TP
\fBboot status\fR
Show whether the boot service is installed and, if enabled, which profile
it uses.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Show current offsets:
\fBsudo ruv-gui status\fR
.TP
Show offsets in JSON format:
\fBsudo ruv-gui status \-\-json\fR
.TP
Get offset for cores 0 through 3:
\fBsudo ruv-gui get 0\-3\fR
.TP
Set core 2 to \-30 mV:
\fBsudo ruv-gui set 2 \-30\fR
.TP
Set all cores 0\-7 to \-40 mV:
\fBsudo ruv-gui set 0\-7 \-40\fR
.TP
Set multiple specific cores:
\fBsudo ruv-gui set 0,2,4 \-25\fR
.TP
Apply same offset to multiple cores without saving:
\fBsudo ruv-gui apply\-list 0\-7 \-50\fR
.TP
Save current settings as a profile:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile save gaming\fR
.TP
List all saved profiles:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile list\fR
.TP
Read a profile's contents:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile read gaming\fR
.TP
Apply a saved profile:
\fBsudo ruv-gui apply gaming\fR
.TP
Update cores in profile "gaming" using range syntax:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile update gaming \-\-cores 0\-3 \-\-offset \-35\fR
.TP
Update specific cores and apply immediately:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile update gaming \-\-cores 0,2,4 \-\-offset \-40 \-\-apply\fR
.TP
Delete a profile:
\fBsudo ruv-gui profile delete oldprofile\fR
.TP
Enable automatic application of "gaming" at boot:
\fBsudo ruv-gui boot enable gaming\fR
.TP
Check boot service status:
\fBsudo ruv-gui boot status\fR
.TP
Disable boot service:
\fBsudo ruv-gui boot disable\fR
.TP
Reset all offsets to 0:
\fBsudo ruv-gui reset\fR

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/ruv/profiles/
Directory where JSON profile files are stored.
.TP
.I /etc/ruv/profiles/*.json
Individual profile files containing core offset mappings.
.TP
.I /etc/systemd/system/ruv\-boot.service
systemd service file created by \fBboot enable\fR.
.TP
.I /sys/kernel/ryzen_smu_drv/
Sysfs interface of the \fBryzen_smu\fR driver.
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin/ruv\-gui
Main executable (symlink to ruv_gui.py).
.TP
.I /usr/share/applications/ruv\-gui.desktop
Desktop entry for the GUI.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\fBRUV_DEBUG\fR=\fI1\fR
Enable verbose debug logging to stderr. Equivalent to \fB\-\-debug\fR.
.TP
\fBQT_LOGGING_RULES\fR
Set to \fBqt.qpa.theme=false\fR by the GUI to suppress Qt theme warnings.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Success.
.TP
1
Error occurred (invalid arguments, driver not loaded, permission denied, etc.)

.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
The tool requires the \fBryzen_smu\fR kernel driver to be loaded.
Load it with \fBsudo modprobe ryzen_smu\fR.
.IP \(bu 2
The GUI should not be run as root; it uses \fBpkexec\fR(1) to elevate
privileges when needed.
.IP \(bu 2
Offset values are in millivolts (mV) and typically negative for undervolting.
The valid range is \-100 to +100 mV.
.IP \(bu 2
Profile names are restricted to alphanumeric characters, underscore,
hyphen, and dot (\fB^[a\-zA\-Z0\-9_.\-]+$\fR).
.IP \(bu 2
The boot service runs after \fBmulti\-user.target\fR and executes once
per boot. Check its status with \fBsystemctl status ruv\-boot.service\fR
or view logs with \fBjournalctl \-u ruv\-boot.service\fR.

.SH SEE ALSO
\fBpkexec\fR(1), \fBsystemctl\fR(1), \fBjournalctl\fR(1), \fBmodprobe\fR(8)
.PP
Ryzen SMU driver: \fIhttps://github.com/amkillam/ryzen_smu\fR
.br
Project repository: \fIhttps://github.com/softwaresocialist/linux\-ryzen\-undervolt\-ui\fR

.SH BUGS
Report issues at the project's issue tracker.
.PP
The tool relies on an out\-of\-tree kernel driver; functionality may vary
across different Ryzen generations. Incorrect offsets may cause system
instability or hardware damage. Use at your own risk.

.SH AUTHOR
Developed with AI assistance. Contributions and feedback welcome.
